<main class="min-h-screen pt-12 pb-24">
    <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
        <nav class="flex space-x-2 mb-8 text-[10px] font-black uppercase tracking-widest text-gray-400">
            <a href="/knowledge-hub" class="hover:text-brand-blue">Knowledge Hub</a>
            <span>/</span>
            <span class="text-gray-900">Banking</span>
        </nav>

        <header class="mb-12">
            <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-8 tracking-tighter leading-tight">
                Best UK Business Banking for <span class="text-brand-blue">Non-Residents (2026)</span>
            </h1>
            <div class="flex items-center space-x-6 p-6 bg-gray-50 rounded-[2rem]">
                <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-full border-2 border-white bg-brand-navy flex items-center justify-center text-white text-[10px] font-black">JS</div>
                <div>
                    <p class="text-gray-900 font-bold text-sm">James Sutherland</p>
                    <p class="text-gray-400 text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-widest">Banking Specialist • March 2026 • 10 min read</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </header>

        <div class="prose prose-blue max-w-none text-gray-600 font-medium space-y-6">
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-900 font-bold leading-relaxed">
                Opening a UK business bank account as a non-resident is the single biggest friction point for international founders. Here's what actually works in 2026.
            </p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">The Banking Landscape in 2026</h2>
            <p>Traditional high-street banks (Barclays, Lloyds, HSBC) still require in-person verification or a UK-resident director for most accounts. For the majority of non-resident founders, this is a non-starter. The good news: the Electronic Money Institution (EMI) market has matured significantly.</p>

            <div class="p-8 bg-blue-50 rounded-[2rem] border-2 border-blue-100 my-8">
                <h4 class="text-brand-blue font-black text-xs uppercase tracking-widest mb-4">The 2026 Reality</h4>
                <p class="text-blue-900 text-sm font-bold">Most non-resident founders should target EMIs (Wise, Revolut, Payoneer) first. Traditional banks can be added later once your company has trading history.</p>
            </div>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Wise Business — Best Overall for Non-Residents</h2>
            <p>Wise Business (formerly TransferWise) has become the default choice for international founders. It supports 40+ currencies with local account details (UK sort code & account number, EU IBAN, US routing number) and can be opened fully online with no UK address required for the account holder.</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
                <li><strong>Approval:</strong> Typically 1–3 business days for most countries.</li>
                <li><strong>Monthly fee:</strong> £0 base fee, pay-as-you-go on transfers.</li>
                <li><strong>FX rates:</strong> Mid-market rate, consistently beats banks.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Revolut Business — Best for Modern Interface</h2>
            <p>Revolut Business is available to UK companies regardless of director residency. The interface is excellent, with spend analytics, team cards, and Xero integration built in. The free plan is suitable for companies with modest transaction volumes.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Tide — Best for UK Residents</h2>
            <p>Tide is integrated with Companies House and can often activate an account within minutes of incorporation for UK residents. For non-residents, Tide's KYC process is more rigorous and approval is less reliable — we recommend Wise or Revolut first.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-10 mb-4">Payoneer — Best for E-Commerce & Freelancers</h2>
            <p>If you operate on Amazon FBA, Upwork, Fiverr, or other platforms, Payoneer is already natively integrated. Their business account provides receiving accounts in 7 currencies and is accessible from virtually any country.</p>

            <div class="bg-gray-900 text-white rounded-[2.5rem] p-10 mt-12">
                <h3 class="text-3xl font-black mb-4 tracking-tighter">Need Help Opening Your Business Account?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400 mb-8 font-medium">Our Banking Assistance service includes document preparation and priority introductions to Wise, Revolut, and more.</p>
                <a href="/services/banking" class="btn-primary inline-block">View Banking Assistance</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>
